SIMPLE: rout
RECORDS: 7

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw> <pr>(rout)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>hr⟦umac⟧tan</ets>.]</ety> <def>To roar; to bellow; to snort; to
snore loudly.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Scot.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bellowing; a shouting; noise;
clamor; uproar; disturbance; tumult.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This new book the whole world makes such a <qex>rout</qex>
about.</q> <rj><qau>Sterne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧My child, it is not well,⟦rdquo⟧ I said,⟦br⟧
⟦ldquo⟧Among the graves to shout;⟦br⟧
To laugh and play among the dead,⟦br⟧
And make this noisy <qex>rout</qex>.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[A variant of
<ets>root</ets>.]</ety> <def>To scoop out with a gouge or other tool; to
furrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To rout out</b></col> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To turn up to
view, as if by rooting; to discover; to find</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
turn out by force or compulsion; as, <xex>to rout</xex> people
<xex>out</xex> of bed.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs> <-- = to root
out, roust out of? -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To search or root in the ground, as
a swine.</def> <rj><au>Edwards.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>route</ets>, LL.
<ets>rupta</ets>, properly, a breaking, fr. L. <ets>ruptus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>rumpere</ets> to break. See <er>Rupture</er>, <er>reave</er>,
and cf. <er>Rote</er> repetition of forms, <er>Route</er>. In some
senses this word has been confused with <ets>rout</ets> a bellowing, an
uproar.]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly spelled also <asp>route</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A troop; a throng; a company; an assembly; especially,
a traveling company or throng.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<xex>route</xex> of ratones [rats].⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Piers Plowman.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧A great solemn <xex>route</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And ever he rode the hinderest of the <qex>route</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>rout</qex> of people there assembled were.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A disorderly and tumultuous crowd; a mob; hence, the
rabble; the herd of common people.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>the endless <qex>routs</qex> of wretched thralls.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ringleader and head of all this <qex>rout</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor do I name of men the common <qex>rout</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being disorganized and thrown into
confusion; -- said especially of an army defeated, broken in pieces, and
put to flight in disorder or panic; also, the act of defeating and
breaking up an army; <as>as, the <ex>rout</ex> of the enemy was
complete</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>thy army . . . ⟦br⟧
Dispersed in <qex>rout</qex>, betook them all to fly.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To these giad conquest, murderous <qex>rout</qex> to those.</q>
<rj><qau>pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A disturbance of the peace by
persons assembled together with intent to do a thing which, if executed,
would make them rioters, and actually making a motion toward the
executing thereof.</def> <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A fashionable assembly, or large evening
party.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧At <xex>routs</xex> and dances.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Landor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To put to rout</b></col>, <cd>to defeat and throw into
confusion; to overthrow and put to flight.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Routed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Routing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To break the ranks of, as troops,
and put them to flight in disorder; to put to rout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That party . . . that charged the Scots, so totally
<qex>routed</qex> and defeated their whole army, that they fied.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To defeat; discomfit; overpower;
overthrow.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Rout
<hw>Rout</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To assemble in a crowd, whether
orderly or disorderly; to collect in company.</def> <mark>[obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In all that land no Christian[s] durste <qex>route</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rout cake</ent>⟦br⟧
